  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>Origin & Range</h3>
    <p>First documented in 1907 by backcountry mycologists, the Tree Trout (<em>Oncorhynchus arboris</em>) is native to high-elevation spruce and fir stands throughout the central Rockies. Sightings peak between $2{,}500$–$3{,}300$ meters where fog drip sustains canopy pools—and where hikers insist they “definitely heard flopping in the branches.”</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>Qualities</h3>
    <p>Adapted for arboreal life: prehensile pectoral fins, bark-mimicking patterning, and a remarkable ability to "leap-ladder" boughs. Reports of “branch-splashing” are considered polite, if unhelpful, scientific observations.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>History & Status</h3>
    <p>Logging, climate shifts, and the decline of epiphytic moss pools have fragmented habitat. Officially, it’s listed as “cryptically threatened,” unofficially as “the fish your uncle swears he saw.”</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>Forest Impact</h3>
    <p>As a keystone detritivore, Tree Trout regulate canopy invertebrates and redistribute nutrients from canopy pools to understory soils—yes, it’s just like a salmon run, except upwards.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>Evolution</h3>
    <p>Phylogenetic models suggest divergence from stream trout during a pluvial period, with selection for vertical niches. It’s the only fish that looked at ladders and said: “That’s habitat.”</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card prose">
    <h3>Relations</h3>
    <p>Co-occurs with canopy salamanders, gliding squirrels, and lesser pine moth. Natural enemies include bald eagles, bored house cats, and gravity.</p>
  </div>
