  <h2>Why It’s Endangered</h2>
  <p>Although not (yet) on official lists, the Tree Trout faces a perfect storm: shrinking fog-drip windows, removal of old-growth moss mats, and the construction of “convenience trails” that incidentally prune the very boughs supporting canopy pools. Also, house cats. Always house cats.</p>
  <p>Route closures that separate fog corridors from spawning creeks further complicate seasonal migrations; gravity remains uncooperative.</p>

  <h2>Past Efforts & Current Status</h2>
  <p>Historic “moss-rescue” campaigns were noble but misguided—turns out moss thrives best when left alone. Today’s best practices emphasize low-impact stewardship and data collection. We’re firmly in the “science with whimsy” phase: careful notes, careful steps, and occasional trout stickers.</p>

  <h2>A Brief History of the Trout Trade</h2>
  <p>Early 20th-century fashion briefly flirted with arbor-fish adornments. Thankfully outlawed, the trend still haunts us in antique shops where “branchfish fascinators” fetch eyebrow-raising bids. We politely suggest fabric ribbons.</p>

  <h2>Sideshow Myths & Folklore</h2>
  <p>Traveling exhibits once depicted Tree Trout as branch-biting nuisances. Modern research suggests they are more likely to spook moths than lumberjacks. If your grandparent insists otherwise, offer hot cocoa and a link to our <a href="/faqs/">FAQs</a>.</p>

  <h2>How You Can Help (Seriously)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Adopt canopy-pool guidelines and share them with your hiking group.</li>
    <li>Participate in <a href="/news/2025-12-01-community-science/">community science</a>.</li>
    <li>Support trail associations that protect epiphytic mats.</li>
    <li>Practice responsible curiosity: observe, don’t disturb.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Evolutionary Notes</h2>
  <p>Modeling suggests an up-branch divergence driven by fog hydrology—sort of a vertical stream. The Tree Trout’s response? “Go up.” Biologists call this “selective optimism.”</p>

  <h2>Relations to Other Creatures</h2>
  <p>Common neighbors include canopy salamanders, gliding squirrels, certain bewildered birds, and the lesser pine moth. Mutualism: moss grooming. Commensalism: seed dispersal (unintentional, we promise).</p>
